This design report summarizes findings regarding concept-level design changes to the
intersection of Spring Gulch Road and Highway 22.
As a part of the area-wide pathways improvements project, several changes were made to
the south side of this intersection, which has since generated complaints from users
regarding large truck movements. It is apparent that certain vehicles are having difficulty
negotiating this intersection without driving onto adjacent traffic lanes.
These changes were made to improve pathway routing through this intersection by
eliminating a free-right slip lane to Spring Gulch Road. This lane was removed and
replaced with a parallel left-turn lane at the intersection with lower overall design speeds
and safer pedestrian interaction. New curb & gutter and two pedestrian ramps on the
south side of the intersection have been installed to date.
This report explains the methodology used to determine the re-design of this intersection,
based on American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials
(AASHTO) design vehicles, site constraints and pedestrian function. A discussion
regarding signalization, striping and signage is also presented.
Teton County desires to construct an intersection that facilitates the movement of large
vehicles to the greatest extent practicable while still considering the goals of Teton
County Pathways. The space available for this project is limited, however, and the
vehicle types that have historically been using this intersection are far larger than the
types originally accommodated (by design) prior to any of these improvements, with the
exception of the free-right slip lane. It is likely that large vehicles have been driving over
adjacent lanes of traffic to accomplish many of these maneuvers, and have been doing so
The preferred alternative concept is attached with this report. Earlier drafts of this
intersection design have been submitted to the State of Wyoming Department of
Transportation (WYDOT) for review, and their comments and recommendations have
Local vehicle type information was obtained from users of this intersection via telephone
interview by Teton County personnel. It appears that the largest vehicle regularly using
this intersection is equivalent to an AASHTO WB-67 tractor-trailer (53ft trailer, 73.5ft
overall) primarily for movements (1) and (2). The next largest vehicles used are
equivalent to a WB-40 tractor trailer (33ft trailer, 45.5ft overall) and a P/T vehicle (27ft
trailer, 48ft overall), which is the closest equivalent to an average horse trailer.
Movements (3) and (4) consider AASHTO WB-40 and P/T vehicles only as WB-67
movements in these directions are unrealistic and, in my opinion, not worth considering
without also considering relocation and reconfiguration of the entire intersection.
All possible traffic movements have been evaluated, which are listed along with the
design vehicle for each maneuver, as follows:
1) Right-turn-in from Highway 22 to Spring Gulch Road (WB-67);
2) Left-turn-out from Spring Gulch Road to Highway 22 (WB-67;
3) Right-turn-out from Spring Gulch Road to Highway 22 (WB-40 & P/T);
4) Left-turn-in from Highway 22 to Spring Gulch Road (WB-40 & P/T)
Perkins Engineering of Salt Lake City was retained to provide AutoTurn software
Traffic count information has been provided by WYDOT, with the most recent data
available collected on a busy day in July 2013. The breakdown by percentages (both cars
Movement (1) – Right-turn-in: 8% of westbound Highway 22 traffic;
Movement (2) – Left-turn-out: 78% of southbound Spring Gulch Road traffic;
Movement (3) – Right-turn-out: 22% of southbound Spring Gulch Road traffic;
Movement (4) – Left-turn-in: 4% of eastbound Highway 22 traffic.
Using AutoTurn simulations, several concepts were developed including re-configuring
the north side of the intersection and removing and replacing portions of the recently
installed curb and gutter. After several iterations it became obvious that a more
significant design adjustment was required, including a separated free-right slip lane, a
separate right turning lane out of Spring Gulch road and modified pedestrian crossing
This latest concept provides several benefits beyond the earlier concepts, including no
off-tracking for critical large-vehicle turning movements, safer and shorter pedestrian
crossings and more standard intersection geometry.
Several proposed speed-reducing features have been incorporated into the free-right slip
lane to improve pedestrian safety, including a raised traffic table, lane narrowing, signage
and striping. The design speed for the free-right turn lane is less than 25 mph, or more
than 10 mph below the posted speed for Spring Gulch Road.
This concept will require removal of the work completed to date. Effort was put toward
keeping the existing work in-place to the greatest extent practicable; however, as the
design progressed and the magnitude of the proposed changes increased, it became a
Exhibits showing the proposed configuration and AutoTurn simulations of all proposed
design vehicle movements are included. AutoTurn software tends to be somewhat
conservative, and larger vehicles than those presented may be able to navigate this
Modifications to the existing intersection signalization will be required to accommodate
the revised lane geometry and to correct several system deficiencies. This work requires
coordination with, and approval from, WYDOT, and is presented here based on concept-
level plans. It is likely that this list of modifications will change somewhat as final
design progresses; they are mentioned here for planning purposes only.
1. Add pole-mounted traffic head for right-turn-out to Highway 22 for a total of two
traffic heads for this movement at the intersection;
2. Change both left-turn-out traffic heads to all left-arrow traffic heads (Manual on
Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD) Section 4) Review comments from
WYDOT recommended new ONLY/ONLY signs next to these signal heads for
turning movements out; however, these added signs may overload the existing
span wires and are not required with all-arrow signal heads per MUTCD.)
3. Add traffic head to existing pole on southeast corner of intersection aiming down
Spring Gulch Road. This should satisfy the MUTCD requirement that at least 2
signal lights be visible 325 feet from an intersection on roads with 35 mph posted
4. Install pole mounted traffic heads and adjust existing traffic heads, pedestrian
heads and crossing buttons to proper vertical clearance per MUTCD, as follows:
Pole-Mounted Signal Heads: 8-feet minimum from sidewalk;
Pedestrian Heads: 9’-3” +/-6” to bottom of signal;
5. Add crossing button to pedestrian signalization system for northbound Spring
Gulch Road crossing. It appears that the button system was not installed when the
utility pole was recently relocated moved.
6. Remove existing pedestrian heads and buttons from the North side of Highway 22
crossing, relocate to proposed crosswalk at the south side.
We anticipate that no major changes to the support structures (poles & span wires) will
be required. These changes will need to be approved by WYDOT, who will provide
structural analysis and signal timing for these changes.
Side street detection is currently being handled by a combined camera & wire sensor
system. We understand that this system is currently un-reliable, requiring people to
periodically exit their vehicle to push the pedestrian button and start the stop cycle for
Highway 22 traffic. WYDOT will provide input on these changes and repairs based on
Several additional signs were recommended by WYDOT, including lane use signs and
street name signs suspended from the existing span wires, as well as ground mounted
signs. We recommend not adding any additional signs to the existing span wires as they
may be overloaded. We recommend using either pole mounted or ground mounted
All required signage will be included in the final design of this interchange, and will meet
the most current standard of Teton County, WYDOT and the MUTCD. Not all required
signs are shown on the latest concept-level plans.
